  "prompt": "Are there specific laws targeting money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are specific laws targeting money laundering in many countries. In the United States, key anti-money laundering (AML) laws include:\n\n1. Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Requires financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Mandates record-keeping and reporting requirements\n\n2. Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- Criminalizes money laundering as a federal offense\n- Establishes penalties for individuals and organizations\n\n3. USA PATRIOT Act\n- Expanded AML regulations after 9/11\n- Increased reporting and monitoring requirements\n- Enhanced cooperation between financial institutions and law enforcement\n\nInternationally, organizations like FATF (Financial Action Task Force) set global standards for combating money laundering. Many countries have similar laws requiring financial institutions to:\n\n- Conduct customer due diligence\n- Report suspicious activities\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement compliance programs\n\nPenalties for money laundering can include:\n- Substantial fines\n- Asset seizure\n- Criminal prosecution\n- Prison sentences\n\nThese laws aim to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income.",
